I wasn&#39;t aware that the Intel compiler is free.  There are two free F90  
compilers that are compatible with gcc.  The first is gfortran, which  
is the official Fortran 90 of the GNU project.  The second one is g95,  
which was originally identical to gfortran but at some point the  
developer of this went his own way.  Both are still in development, but  
seem to be complete enough to handle most Fortran 90 application  
programs.  I have found it a little easier to get gfortran running, but  
both work.

When you run the Cantera &#39;configure&#39; script, it detects which f90  
compiler you have and sets the compiler options for it automatically.   
(It detects several commercial f90 compilers too.) After building  
Cantera, you should be able to do this to build and run the Fortran 90  
demo program:

source ~/setup_cantera
ctnew -f90
make -f demo.mak
./demo

Here are the web sites:
http://www.gfortran.org
http://g95.sourceforge.net

You may need Cantera 1.6.0 for this to work. If so, you can get it by  
anonymous CVS as described in a previous message. (Someday I hope to  
get around to finishing version 1.6.0 and actually releasing it...)

Dave


